{
  "text": "After entering the body from an exogenous source, Cr 3+ binds to plasma proteins such as transferrin, an iron-transporting protein. Regardless of the source, Cr 3+ is widely distributed in the body and accounts for most of the chromium in plasma or tissues. The Cr 3+ is taken up as a protein complex into bone marrow, lungs, lymph nodes, spleen, kidney, and liver, with the highest uptake being in the lungs [CITATION_1] . It has been shown that cell membranes are relatively impermeable to Cr 3+ . When varying amounts of radioactive Cr 3+ were added to whole blood in vitro, almost all of the radioactivity (94%-99%) remained in the plasma with an insignificant amount retained in the red blood cells (RBC). Similar results were obtained in vivo [CITATION_2] . Similarly, low permeability of Cr 3+ was found in Chinese hamster lung V79 cells exposed to Cr 3+ complexes [CITATION_3] . Additionally, it has been shown that the cellular uptake of Cr 6+ is several-fold greater than that of Cr 3+ ion, because trivalent chromium is predominantly octahedral and diffuses slowly [CITATION_4] . Excretion of Cr occurs primarily via urine, with no major retention in organs. Approximately 10% of an absorbed dose is eliminated by biliary excretion, with smaller amounts excreted in hair, nails, milk, and sweat. Clearance from plasma is generally rapid (within hours), whereas elimination from tissues is slower (with a half-life of several days) [CITATION_5] .",
  "correct_citation": {
